+| SEC-006 | Critical | `booking/serializers.py`, `booking/views/bookings.py`, `booking/manage_partner_booking.py` | Booking APIs disclose the opposite party's session token in customer and partner responses, creating a direct cross-role impersonation path between customers and operators. | open | Source inspection during security-audit Phase 1 |
+| SEC-007 | Critical | `common/user_profile.py`, `common/serializers.py`, `partners/partner_profile.py`, `partners/serializers.py` | Public existence/profile endpoints return full serialized user and partner records, including session tokens and Firebase device tokens, instead of safe yes/no lookup results. | open | Source inspection during security-audit Phase 1 |
+| SEC-008 | Critical | `common/user_profile.py`, `common/utility.py`, `common/authentication.py` | Customer `session_token` values are deterministically derived from phone numbers with base64 encoding and are accepted by the auth bridge, so any known phone number can be turned into a bearer-equivalent token offline. | open | Source inspection during security-audit Phase 1 |
+| SEC-009 | Critical | `partners/partner_accounts_and_transactions.py` | The partner bank-account and withdrawal endpoints are `AllowAny` and keyed only by `partner_session_token`; an attacker who learns a token can register their own payout account and submit a withdrawal that immediately debits the victim wallet. | open | Source inspection during security-audit Phase 1 |
+| SEC-010 | High | `booking/manage_partner_booking.py` | Several partner booking mutation endpoints still load the target partner from `request.data['partner_session_token']` instead of the already-authenticated principal, so leaked tokens can be replayed to mutate another partner's bookings. | open | Source inspection during security-audit Phase 1 |
